I"8<p>CalyxOS Emulator images are now available, which can be used with the Emulator present in Android Studio.</p>

<p>Theyâ€™re mostly meant for testing apps (especially system included apps such as Datura and Seedvault). Theyâ€™re <em>not</em> meant for general usage.</p>

<p>URL: <a href="https://release.calyxinstitute.org/sys-img.xml">https://release.calyxinstitute.org/sys-img.xml</a></p>

<p>These images are <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">userdebug</code> which means you can use <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">adb root</code>.</p>

<p>Additionally, these arenâ€™t separately signed, which means all the apps are signed using publicly available AOSP â€œtest-keysâ€, meaning that you can easily test code changes to system apps.</p>

<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">x86</code> and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">x86_64</code> images are available currently. <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">arm64</code> images appear to be currently broken in AOSP, however weâ€™re trying to see if we can fix them. Those will be made available when ready.</p>

<h3 id="steps">Steps</h3>

<p>This emulator image is meant for use with <a href="https://developer.android.com/studio">Android Studio</a></p>

<ol>
  <li>Launch Android Studio, and open Tools -&gt; SDK Manager</li>
  <li>Click on â€œSDK Update Sitesâ€, and then tap the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">+</code> plus icon on the left.</li>
  <li>Type in the above url, i.e. <a href="https://release.calyxinstitute.org/sys-img.xml">https://release.calyxinstitute.org/sys-img.xml</a> and under name enter â€œCalyxOSâ€</li>
  <li>Make sure the checkbox to the left of â€œCalyxOSâ€ is checked, and then hit Apply or OK.</li>
  <li>You can now create an AVD with the CalyxOS image.</li>
  <li>Open â€œTools -&gt; AVD Managerâ€</li>
  <li>Click â€œCreate Virtual Deviceâ€ at the bottom, then select hardware.</li>
  <li>Next, on the â€œSystem Imageâ€ selection page, click on â€œx86 Imagesâ€.</li>
  <li>You should see the CalyxOS Images, they will show up as Target: Android 11 (CalyxOS Android System Image).</li>
  <li>Click â€œDownloadâ€ to download the system image, and then hit next.</li>
  <li>You can now launch the AVD to run CalyxOS.</li>
</ol>

<p>These images will get updated every month as we tag and release new builds.</p>

<h3 id="sdkmanager-installation">sdkmanager installation</h3>

<p>If you want to install these images using sdkmanager, the strings are:</p>
<ul>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">"system-images;android-30;calyx;x86"</code></li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">"system-images;android-30;calyx;x86_64"</code></li>
</ul>

<h3 id="docker-images">Docker images</h3>

<p>F-Droid has CI images which have the Android SDK pre-configured with our repos.
Theyâ€™re included in the docker image: <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">registry.gitlab.com/fdroid/ci-images-client</code>
This means that this can be used to directly install the CalyxOS images and use it for testing / CI.</p>

<p>For more details see: <a href="https://gitlab.com/fdroid/ci-images-client">https://gitlab.com/fdroid/ci-images-client</a></p>

